# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: microstrip-design
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:microstrip-design/coplanar-waveguide] Coplanar waveguide is a type of electrical planar transmission line which can be fabricated using printed circuit board technology, and is used to convey microwave-frequency signals.
[src:microstrip-design/coplanar-waveguide] On a smaller scale, coplanar waveguide transmission lines are also built into monolithic microwave integrated circuits.
[src:microstrip-design/coplanar-waveguide] Conventional **coplanar waveguide** (**CPW**) consists of a single conducting track printed onto a dielectric substrate, together with a pair of return conductors, one to either side of the track.
[src:microstrip-design/coplanar-waveguide] All three conductors are on the same side of the substrate, and hence are *coplanar*.
[src:microstrip-design/coplanar-waveguide] The return conductors are separated from the central track by a small gap, which has an unvarying width along the length of the line.
[src:microstrip-design/coplanar-waveguide] Away from the central conductor, the return conductors usually extend to an indefinite but large distance, so that each is notionally a semi-infinite plane.
[src:microstrip-design/coplanar-waveguide] Coplanar waveguide was invented in 1969 by Cheng P.
[src:microstrip-design/coplanar-waveguide] Wen, primarily as a means by which non-reciprocal components such as gyrators and isolators could be incorporated in planar transmission line circuits.
[src:microstrip-design/coplanar-waveguide] The electromagnetic wave carried by a coplanar waveguide exists partly in the dielectric substrate, and partly in the air above it.
[src:microstrip-design/coplanar-waveguide] In general, the dielectric constant of the substrate will be different (and greater) than that of the air, so that the wave is travelling in an inhomogeneous medium.
[src:microstrip-design/coplanar-waveguide] In consequence CPW will not support a true TEM wave; at non-zero frequencies, both the E and H fields will have longitudinal components (a hybrid mode).
[src:microstrip-design/coplanar-waveguide] However, these longitudinal components are usually small and the mode is better described as quasi-TEM.
[src:microstrip-design/coplanar-waveguide] Nonreciprocal gyromagnetic devices such as resonant isolators and differential phase shifters depend on a microwave signal presenting a rotating (circularly polarized) magnetic field to a statically magnetized ferrite body.
[src:microstrip-design/coplanar-waveguide] CPW can be designed to produce just such a rotating magnetic field in the two slots between the central and side conductors.
[src:microstrip-design/coplanar-waveguide] The dielectric substrate has no direct effect on the magnetic field of a microwave signal travelling along the CPW line.
[src:microstrip-design/coplanar-waveguide] For the magnetic field, the CPW is then symmetrical in the plane of the metalization, between the substrate side and the air side.
[src:microstrip-design/coplanar-waveguide] Consequently, currents flowing along parallel paths on opposite faces of each conductor (on the air-side and on the substrate-side) are subject to the same inductance, and the overall current tends to be divided equally between the two faces.
[src:microstrip-design/coplanar-waveguide] Conversely, the substrate *does* affect the electric field, so that the substrate side contributes a larger capacitance across the slots than does the air side.
[src:microstrip-design/coplanar-waveguide] Electric charge can accumulate or be depleted more readily on the substrate face of the conductors than on the air face.
[src:microstrip-design/coplanar-waveguide] As a result, at those points on the wave where the current reverses direction, charge will spill over the edges of the metalization between the air face and the substrate face.
[src:microstrip-design/coplanar-waveguide] This secondary current over the edges gives rise to a longitudinal (parallel with the line), magnetic field in each of the slots, which is in quadrature with the vertical (normal to the substrate surface) magnetic field associated with the main current along the conductors.
[src:microstrip-design/coplanar-waveguide] If the dielectric constant of the substrate is much greater than unity, then the magnitude of the longitudinal magnetic field approaches that of the vertical field, so that the combined magnetic field in the slots approaches circular polarization.
[src:microstrip-design/coplanar-waveguide] Coplanar waveguides play an important role in the field of solid state quantum computing, e.g. for the coupling of microwave photons to a superconducting qubit.
[src:microstrip-design/coplanar-waveguide] To further enhance this coupling, superconducting coplanar waveguide resonators with extremely low losses were applied.
[src:microstrip-design/coplanar-waveguide] (The quality factors of such superconducting coplanar resonators at low temperatures can exceed 106 even in the low-power limit.) Coplanar resonators can also be employed as quantum buses to couple multiple qubits to each other.
[src:microstrip-design/coplanar-waveguide] Another application of coplanar waveguides in solid state research is for studies involving magnetic resonance, e.g. for electron spin resonance spectroscopy or for magnonics.
[src:microstrip-design/coplanar-waveguide] Coplanar waveguide resonators have also been employed to characterize the material properties of (high-Tc) superconducting thin films.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-antenna] In telecommunication, a **microstrip antenna** (also known as a **printed antenna**) usually is an antenna fabricated using photolithographic techniques on a printed circuit board (PCB).
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-antenna] They are mostly used at microwave frequencies.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-antenna] An individual microstrip antenna consists of a patch of metal foil of various shapes (a patch antenna) on the surface of a PCB, with a metal foil ground plane on the other side of the board.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-antenna] Most microstrip antennas consist of multiple patches in a two-dimensional array.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-antenna] The antenna is usually connected to the transmitter or receiver through foil microstrip transmission lines.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-antenna] The radio-frequency current is applied (or in receiving antennas the received signal is produced) between the antenna and ground plane.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-antenna] Based on its origin, microstrip consists of two words, namely micro (very thin/small) and is defined as a type of antenna that has a blade/piece shape and is very thin/small.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-antenna] The most common type of microstrip antenna is commonly known as patch antenna.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-antenna] Antennas using patches as constitutive elements in an array are also possible.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-antenna] A patch antenna is a narrowband, wide-beam antenna fabricated by etching the antenna element pattern in metal trace bonded to an insulating dielectric substrate, such as a printed circuit board, with a continuous metal layer bonded to the opposite side of the substrate which forms a ground plane.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-antenna] Common microstrip antenna shapes are square, rectangular, circular and elliptical, but any continuous shape is possible.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-antenna] Some patch antennas do not use a dielectric substrate and instead are made of a metal patch mounted above a ground plane using dielectric spacers; the resulting structure is less rugged but has a wider bandwidth.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-antenna] Because such antennas have a very low profile, are mechanically rugged and can be shaped to conform to the curving skin of a vehicle, they are often mounted on the exterior of aircraft and spacecraft, or are incorporated into mobile radio communications devices.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-antenna] Microstrip antennas are relatively inexpensive to manufacture and design because of the simple two-dimensional physical geometry.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-antenna] They are usually employed at UHF and higher frequencies because the size of the antenna is directly tied to the wavelength at the resonant frequency.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-antenna] A single patch antenna provides a maximum directive gain of around 6–9 dBi.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-antenna] It is relatively easy to print an array of patches on a single (large) substrate using lithographic techniques.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-antenna] Patch arrays can provide much higher gains than a single patch at little additional cost; matching and phase adjustment can be performed with printed microstrip feed structures, again in the same operations that form the radiating patches.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-antenna] The ability to create high gain arrays in a low-profile antenna is one reason that patch arrays are common on airplanes and in other military applications.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-antenna] Such an array of patch antennas is an easy way to make a phased array of antennas with dynamic beamforming ability.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-antenna] An advantage inherent to patch antennas is the ability to have polarization diversity.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-antenna] Patch antennas can easily be designed to have vertical, horizontal, right hand circular (RHCP) or left hand circular (LHCP) polarizations, using multiple feed points, or a single feedpoint with asymmetric patch structures.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-antenna] This unique property allows patch antennas to be used in many types of communications links that may have varied requirements.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-antenna] The most commonly employed microstrip antenna is a rectangular patch which looks like a truncated microstrip transmission line.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-antenna] It is approximately of one-half wavelength long.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-antenna] When air is used as the dielectric substrate, the length of the rectangular microstrip antenna is approximately one-half of a free-space wavelength.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-antenna] As the antenna is loaded with a dielectric as its substrate, the length of the antenna decreases as the relative dielectric constant of the substrate increases.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-antenna] The resonant length of the antenna is slightly shorter because of the extended electric "fringing fields" which increase the electrical length of the antenna slightly.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-antenna] An early model of the microstrip antenna is a section of microstrip transmission line with equivalent loads on either end to represent the radiation loss.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-antenna] The dielectric loading of a microstrip antenna affects both its radiation pattern and impedance bandwidth.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-antenna] As the dielectric constant of the substrate increases, the antenna bandwidth decreases which increases the Q factor of the antenna and therefore decreases the impedance bandwidth.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-antenna] This relationship did not immediately follow when using the transmission line model of the antenna, but is apparent when using the cavity model which was introduced in 1973 by Itoh and Mittra The radiation from a rectangular microstrip antenna may be understood as a pair of equivalent slots.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-antenna] These slots act as an array and have the highest directivity when the antenna has an air dielectric and decreases when it is replaced by a dielectric substrate with increasing relative permittivity.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-antenna] The half-wave rectangular microstrip antenna has a virtual shorting plane along its center.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-antenna] This may be replaced with a physical shorting plane to create a quarter-wavelength microstrip antenna.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-antenna] The antenna only has a single radiation edge (equivalent slot) which lowers the directivity/gain of the antenna.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-antenna] The impedance bandwidth is slightly lower than a half-wavelength full patch as the coupling between radiating edges has been eliminated.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-antenna] Another type of patch antenna is the planar inverted-F antenna (PIFA).
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-antenna] The PIFA is common in cellular phones (mobile phones) as a built-in structure.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-antenna] These antennas are derived from a quarter-wave half-patch antenna.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-antenna] The shorting plane of the half-patch is reduced in length which decreases the resonance frequency.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-antenna] It offers a low profile and also with acceptable SAR properties.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-antenna] This antenna resembles an inverted F, which explains the PIFA name.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-antenna] It is popular as a compact antenna with an omnidirectional pattern.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-antenna] Often PIFA antennas have multiple branches to resonate at the various cellular bands.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-antenna] On some phones, grounded parasitic elements are used to enhance the radiation bandwidth characteristics.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-antenna] The folded inverted conformal antenna (FICA) has some advantages with respect to the PIFA, because it allows better volume reuse.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-antenna] Defected Ground Structure (DGS)-integrated microstrip patch has been popular for multiple purposes.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-antenna] This technique introduces a limited number of small-sized slots, termed as 'defects' on the ground plane beneath the patch, and is potentially capable of improving its far-field as well as near-field properties.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-antenna] This was conceived and introduced in 2005 by Guha to control the cross-polarized radiations without involving any extra component, volume, weight, or cost.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-antenna] The technique is advanced enough to reduce cross-polarized radiations even over the diagonal-planes of a microstrip patch.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-antenna] DGS-technique is equally effective in reducing the mutual coupling in large microstrip arrays and hence mitigating the scan blindness issue of the radar beams.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-antenna] The DGS technique is found to be highly attractive in air-borne applications.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-line] Typical realisation technologies are printed circuit board (PCB), alumina coated with a dielectric layer or sometimes silicon or some other similar technologies.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-line] Microwave components such as antennas, couplers, filters, power dividers etc. can be formed from microstrip, with the entire device existing as the pattern of metallization on the substrate.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-line] Microstrip is thus much less expensive than traditional waveguide technology, as well as being far lighter and more compact.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-line] Microstrip was developed by ITT laboratories as a competitor to stripline (first published by Grieg and Engelmann in the December 1952 IRE proceedings).
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-line] The disadvantages of microstrip compared with waveguide is the generally lower power handling capacity, and higher losses.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-line] Also, unlike waveguide, microstrip is typically not enclosed, and is therefore susceptible to cross-talk and unintentional radiation.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-line] For lowest cost, microstrip devices may be built on an ordinary FR-4 (standard PCB) substrate.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-line] However it is often found that the dielectric losses in FR4 are too high at microwave frequencies, and that the dielectric constant is not sufficiently tightly controlled.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-line] For these reasons, an alumina substrate is commonly used.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-line] From monolithic integration perspective microstrips with integrated circuit/monolithic microwave integrated circuit technologies might be feasible however their performance might be limited by the dielectric layer(s) and conductor thickness available.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-line] Microstrip lines are also used in high-speed digital PCB designs, where signals need to be routed from one part of the assembly to another with minimal distortion, and avoiding high cross-talk and radiation.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-line] Microstrip is one of many forms of planar transmission line, others include stripline and coplanar waveguide, and it is possible to integrate all of these on the same substrate.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-line] A differential microstrip—a balanced signal pair of microstrip lines—is often used for high-speed signals such as DDR2 SDRAM clocks, USB Hi-Speed data lines, PCI Express data lines, LVDS data lines, etc., often all on the same PCB.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-line] Most PCB design tools support such differential pairs.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-line] The electromagnetic wave carried by a microstrip line exists partly in the dielectric substrate, and partly in the air above it.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-line] In consequence, the propagation velocity is somewhere between the speed of radio waves in the substrate, and the speed of radio waves in air.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-line] This behaviour is commonly described by stating the effective dielectric constant of the microstrip; this being the dielectric constant of an equivalent homogeneous medium (i.e., one resulting in the same propagation velocity).
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-line] Here *Z*0 is the impedance of free space, *ε*r is the relative permittivity of substrate, *w* is the width of the strip, *h* is the thickness ("height") of substrate, and *t* is the thickness of the strip metallization.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-line] It is claimed that for most other cases, the error in impedance is less than 1%, and is always less than 2%.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-line] By covering all aspect-ratios in one formula, Wheeler 1977 improves on Wheeler 1965 which gives one formula for *w*/*h* > 3.3 and another for *w*/*h* ≤ 3.3 (thus introducing a discontinuity in the result at *w*/*h* = 3.3).
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-line] Harold Wheeler disliked both the terms 'microstrip' and 'characteristic impedance', and avoided using them in his papers.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-line] A number of other approximate formulae for the characteristic impedance have been advanced by other authors.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-line] However, most of these are applicable to only a limited range of aspect-ratios, or else cover the entire range piecewise.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-line] Microstrip circuits may require a metallic enclosure, depending upon the application.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-line] If the top cover of the enclosure encroaches in the microstrip, the characteristic impedance of the microstrip may be reduced due to the additional path for plate and fringing capacitance.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-line] When this happens, equations have been developed to adjust the characteristic impedance in air (*ε*r = 1) of the microstrip, $\Delta Z_{om}^{a}$ , where $Z_{om}^{a}=Z_{o\infty }^{a}-\Delta Z_{om}^{a}$ , and $Z_{o\infty }^{a}$ is the impedance of the uncovered microstrip in air.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-line] Equations for $\varepsilon _{re}$ may be adjusted to account for the metallic cover and used to compute Zo with dielectric using the expression, $Z_{om}=Z_{om}^{a}/{\sqrt {\varepsilon _{re_{m}}}}$ , where $\varepsilon _{re_{m}}$ is the $\varepsilon _{re}$ adjusted for the metallic cover.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-line] Finite strip thickness compensation may be computed by substituting $w_{\textrm {eff}}$ from above for w for both $\Delta Z_{om}^{a}$ and $\varepsilon _{re_{m}}$ calculations, using $\varepsilon =1$ all air calculations and $\varepsilon =\varepsilon _{r}$ for all dielectric material calculations.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-line] In the below expressions, c is the cover height, the distance from the top of the dielectric to the metallic cover.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-line] When the dielectric layer is suspended over the lower ground plane by an air layer, the substrate is known as a suspended substrate, which is analogous to the layer D in the microstrip illustration at the top right of the page being nonzero.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-line] The advantages of using a suspended substrate over a traditional microstrip are reduced dispersion effects, increased design frequencies, wider strip geometries, reduced structural inaccuracies, more precise electrical properties, and a higher obtainable characteristic impedance.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-line] The disadvantage is that suspended substrates are larger than traditional microstrip substrates, and are more difficult to manufacture.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-line] When the conductor is placed below the dielectric layer, as opposed to above, the microstrip is known as an inverted microstrip.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-line] Pramanick and Bhartia documented a series of equations used to approximate the characteristic impedance (Zo) and effective dielectric constant (Ere) for suspended and inverted microstrips.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-line] The equations are accessible directly from the reference and are not repeated here.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-line] John Smith worked out equations for the even and odd mode fringe capacitance for arrays of coupled microstrip lines in a suspended substrate using Fourier series expansion of the charge distribution, and provides 1960s style Fortran code that performs the function.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-line] Smith's work is detailed in the section below.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-line] Single single microstrip lines behave like coupled microstrips with infinitely wide gaps.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-line] Inverted microstrips may be computed by swapping the cover height and suspended height variables.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-line] Microstrips with no metallic enclosure may be computed by entering a large variable into the metallic cover height such that the metallic cover no longer significantly effects the microstrip electrical characteristics, typically 50 or more times the height of the conductor over the substrate.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-line] Inverted microstrips may be computed by swapping the metallic cover height and suspended height variables.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-line] where B, C, and D are defined by the microstrip geometry that is shown in the upper right of the page.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-line] In order to build a complete circuit in microstrip, it is often necessary for the path of a strip to turn through a large angle.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-line] An abrupt 90° bend in a microstrip will cause a significant portion of the signal on the strip to be reflected back towards its source, with only part of the signal transmitted on around the bend.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-line] One means of effecting a low-reflection bend, is to curve the path of the strip in an arc of radius at least 3 times the strip-width.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-line] However, a far more common technique, and one which consumes a smaller area of substrate, is to use a mitred bend.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-line] To a first approximation, an abrupt un-mitred bend behaves as a shunt capacitance placed between the ground plane and the bend in the strip.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-line] Mitring the bend reduces the area of metallization, and so removes the excess capacitance.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-line] The percentage mitre is the cut-away fraction of the diagonal between the inner and outer corners of the un-mitred bend.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-line] The optimum mitre for a wide range of microstrip geometries has been determined experimentally by Douville and James.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-line] subject to *w*/*h* ≥ 0.25 and with the substrate dielectric constant *ε*r ≤ 25.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-line] This formula is entirely independent of *ε*r.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-line] The actual range of parameters for which Douville and James present evidence is 0.25 ≤ *w*/*h* ≤ 2.75 and 2.5 ≤ *ε*r ≤ 25.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-line] They report a VSWR of better than 1.1 (i.e., a return loss better than −26 dB) for any percentage mitre within 4% (of the original *d*) of that given by the formula.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-line] At the minimum *w*/*h* of 0.25, the percentage mitre is 98.4%, so that the strip is very nearly cut through.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-line] For both the curved and mitred bends, the electrical length is somewhat shorter than the physical path-length of the strip.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-line] Other types of microstrip discontinuities besides bends (see above), also referred to as corners, are open ends, via holes (connections to the ground plane), steps in width, gaps between microstrips, tee junctions, and cross junctions.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-line] Extensive work has been performed developing models for these types of junctions, and are documented in publicly available literature, such as Quite universal circuit simulator (QUCS).
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-line] Microstrip lines may be installed close enough to other microstrip lines such that electrical coupling interactions may exist between the lines.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-line] This may come about inadvertently as lines are laid out, or intentionally to shape a desired transfer function, or design a distributed filter.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-line] If the two lines are identical in width, they may be characterized by a coupled transmission line even and odd mode analysis.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-line] Closed form expressions for even and odd mode characteristic impedance (Zoe, Zoo) and effective dielectric constant (*ε*ree, *ε*reo) have been developed with defined accuracy under stated conditions.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-line] They are available from the references and not repeated here.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-line] John Smith worked out equations for the even and odd mode fringe capacitance for arrays of coupled microstrip lines with a metallic cover including suspended microstrips using Fourier series expansion of the charge distribution, and provides 1960s style Fortran code that performs the function.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-line] Uncovered microstrips are supported by assigning a cover height of generally 50 or more times the conductor height above the ground plane.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-line] Inverted microstrips are supported by reversing the cover height and suspended height variables.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-line] Smiths equations are advantageous in that they are theoretically valid for all values of conductor width, conductor separation, dielectric constant, cover height, and dielectric suspension height.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-line] Smith's equations contain a bottleneck (equation 37 on page 429) where the inverse of an elliptic integral ratio must be solved, $K(1,{\sqrt {1-k^{2}}})/K(1,k)=X$ , where $K(,)$ is the complete elliptic integral of the first kind, X is known, and k is the variable that must be solved.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-line] Smith provides an elaborate search algorithm that usually converges on a solution for k .
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-line] However, Newton's method or interpolation tables may provide a more rapid and comprehensive solution for k .
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-line] To compute the even and odd mode Zo and εre values for an uncoupled microstrip, the plate capacitance is added to the even and odd mode fringe capacitance for the inside of the microstrip and the uncoupled fringe capacitance of the outer sides.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-line] Smith's Fourier series requires the inverse solution, ***k***, to the elliptic integral ratio, $K({\sqrt {1-k^{2}}})/K(k)$ , where *K*() is the complete elliptic integral of the first kind.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-line] Although Smith provides an elaborate search algorithm to find ***k***, faster and more accurate convergence may be achieved with Newton's method, or interpolation tables may be employed.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-line] Once the value *klg* is solved for, *k* is obtained by $k=e^{k_{lg}}$ .
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-line] The Newton's method expression to solve for *klg* is as follows using standard derivative rules.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-line] An interpolation table to find *klg* and *k* is shown below.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-line] For values of $F(x)<1$ , it is useful to apply the relation shown in the table to maximize the linearity of the $k_{lg}$ , or $ln(k)$ , function for use in Newton's method or interpolation.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-line] To compute the value of the total even and odd mode capacitance based on Smith's work using elliptic integrals and jacobi elliptic functions.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-line] Smith uses the third fast Jacobi elliptic function estimation algorithm found in the elliptic functions page.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-line] where $(G=\infty )$ may be approximated by $(G=7)$ or more times the conductor height above the ground plane.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-line] Smith compares the accuracy of his Fourier series capacitance solutions to published tables of the times.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-line] However, a more modern approach is to compare the even and odd mode impedance and effective dielectric constants results to those obtains from electromagnetic simulations such as Sonnet.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-line] The below example is performed under the following conditions: B = 2.5 mm, C = 0.4 mm, D = 0.6 mm, W = 1.5 mm, G = 0.5 mm, Er = 12, where B, C, and D are defined by the microstrip geometry that is shown in the upper right of the page.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-line] The example begins by computing the value of log(*k*), then *k*, and goes on to use *k*, *ε*r, substrate geometry, and conductor geometry to compute the capacitances and subsequently the even and odd mode impedance and effective dielectric constant (*Z*oe, *Z*oo, *ε*re and *ε*ro).
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-line] The Sonnet simulation is performed with a high resolution grid resolution of 4096 × 4096, reference planes of 7 mm on each side, and simulates the coupled line along a 10 mm length.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-line] The Y parameters results are translated to even and odd mode *Z*o and *ε*r by algebraically inverting the Y parameter equations for coupled transmission lines.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-line] When two microstrip lines exist close enough in proximity for coupling to occur but are not symmetrical in width, even and odd mode analysis is not directly applicable to characterize the lines.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-line] In this case, the lines are generally characterized by their self and mutual inductance and capacitance.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-line] The defining techniques and expressions are available from the references.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-line] In some cases, multiple microstrip lines may be coupled together.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-line] When this happens, each microstrip line will have a self capacitance and a gap capacitance to all of the other lines, including nonadjacent microstrips.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-line] Analysis is similar to the asymmetric coupled case above, but the capacitance and inductance matrices will be of size NXN, where N is the number of microstrips coupled together.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-line] Nonadjacent microstrip capacitance may be accurately calculated using the Finite element method (FEM).
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-line] Attenuation due to losses from the conductor and dielectric are generally considered when simulating a microstrip.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-line] Total losses are a function of microstrip length, so attenuation is generally calculated in units of attenuation per unit length, with total losses calculated by attenuation × length, with attenuation units of Nepers, although some applications may use attenuation in units dB.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-line] When the microstrip characteristic impedance (Zo), effective dielectric constant (Ere), and total losses ( $\alpha l$ ) are all known the microstrip may be modeled as a standard transmission line.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-line] Conductor losses are defined by the "specific resistance" or "resistivity" of the conductor material, and generally expressed as $\rho$ in the literature.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-line] Each conductor material generally has a published resistivity associated with it.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-line] For example, the common conductor material of copper has a published resistivity of 1.68×10−8 Ω⋅m.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-line] Note that if surface roughness is neglected, the $K_{\text{r}}$ disappears from the expression, and it frequently is.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-line] Some authors use conductor thickness instead of skin depth to compute the sheet resistance, *R*s.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-line] Dielectric losses are defined by the "loss tangent" of the dielectric material, and generally expressed as $tan\delta _{d}$ in the literature.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-line] Each dielectric material generally has a published loss tangent associated with it.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-line] For example, the common dielectric material is alumina has a published loss tangent of 0.0002 to 0.0003 depending on the frequency.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-line] Dielectric losses are in general much less than conductor losses and are frequently neglected in some applications.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-line] Coupled microstrip losses may be estimated using the same even and odd mode analysis as is used for characteristic impedance, dielectric constant. and effective dielectric constant for single line microstrips.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-line] Coupled line even mode and odd mode each have their independently calculated conductor and dielectric loss values calculated from the corresponding single line Zo and Ere.
[src:microstrip-design/microstrip-line] The partial derivatives with respect to the conductor's separation, thickness, and width may be calculated digitally.
[src:microstrip-design/stripline] In electronics, **stripline** is a transverse electromagnetic (TEM) transmission line medium invented by Robert M.
[src:microstrip-design/stripline] Barrett of the Air Force Cambridge Research Centre in the 1950s.
[src:microstrip-design/stripline] Stripline is the earliest form of planar transmission line.
[src:microstrip-design/stripline] A stripline circuit uses a flat strip of metal which is sandwiched between two parallel ground planes.
[src:microstrip-design/stripline] The insulating material of the substrate forms a dielectric.
[src:microstrip-design/stripline] The width of the strip, the thickness of the substrate and the relative permittivity of the substrate determine the characteristic impedance of the strip which is a transmission line.
[src:microstrip-design/stripline] As shown in the diagram, the central conductor need not be equally spaced between the ground planes.
[src:microstrip-design/stripline] In the general case, the dielectric material may be different above and below the central conductor.
[src:microstrip-design/stripline] A stripline that uses air as the dielectric material is known as an air stripline.
[src:microstrip-design/stripline] To prevent the propagation of unwanted modes, the two ground planes must be shorted together.
[src:microstrip-design/stripline] This is commonly achieved by a row of vias running parallel to the strip on each side.
[src:microstrip-design/stripline] Like coaxial cable, stripline is non-dispersive, and has no cutoff frequency.
[src:microstrip-design/stripline] Good isolation between adjacent traces can be achieved more easily than with microstrip.
[src:microstrip-design/stripline] Stripline provides for enhanced noise immunity against the propagation of radiated RF emissions, at the expense of slower propagation speeds when compared to microstrip lines.
[src:microstrip-design/stripline] The effective permittivity of striplines equals the relative permittivity of the dielectric substrate because of wave propagation only in the substrate.
[src:microstrip-design/stripline] Stripline was initially preferred to its rival, microstrip, made by ITT.
[src:microstrip-design/stripline] Transmission in stripline is purely TEM mode and consequently there is no dispersion (provided that the dielectric of substrate is not itself dispersive).
[src:microstrip-design/stripline] Also, discontinuity elements on the line (gaps, stubs, posts etc) present a purely reactive impedance.
[src:microstrip-design/stripline] This is not the case with microstrip; the differing dielectrics above and below the strip result in longitudinal non-TEM components to the wave.
[src:microstrip-design/stripline] This results in dispersion and discontinuity elements have a resistive component causing them to radiate.
[src:microstrip-design/stripline] In the 1950s Eugene Fubini, at the time working for AIL, jokingly suggested that a microstrip dipole would make a good antenna.
[src:microstrip-design/stripline] This was intended to highlight the drawbacks of microstrip, but the microstrip patch antenna has become the most popular design of antenna in mobile devices.
[src:microstrip-design/stripline] Stripline remained in the ascendent for its performance advantages through the 1950s and 1960s but eventually microstrip won out, especially in mass produced items, because it was easier to assemble and the lack of an upper dielectric meant that components were easier to access and adjust.
[src:microstrip-design/stripline] As the complexity of printed circuits increased, this convenience issue became more important until today microstrip is the dominant planar technology.
[src:microstrip-design/stripline] Miniaturisation also leads to favouring microstrip because its disadvantages are not so severe in a miniaturised circuit.
[src:microstrip-design/stripline] However, stripline is still chosen where operation over a wide band is required.
[src:microstrip-design/stripline] Microstrip is similar to stripline transmission line except that the microstrip is not sandwiched, it is on a surface layer, above a ground plane.
[src:microstrip-design/stripline] Stripline is more expensive to fabricate than microstrip, and because of the second groundplane, the strip widths are much narrower for a given impedance and board thickness than for microstrip.
[src:microstrip-design/stripline] Note that when the conductor thickness is small, T<<1 or t<<h, the equations simplify significantly.
[src:microstrip-design/stripline] The accuracy of the formula is claimed to be at least 1% for W/(H-T) > .05 and T< 0.025.
[src:microstrip-design/stripline] Where T and W are as defined the same as the above expression.
[src:microstrip-design/stripline] The accuracy is claimed to be at least 0.5% for C>0.25.
[src:microstrip-design/stripline] For stripline conductors that are not centered, that is, the distance to the upper ground plane is not the same as to the lower ground plane, strategies exist to estimate the characteristic impedance in at least one of two ways.
[src:microstrip-design/stripline] The $Z_{o}$ of each stripline may be evaluated independently, and the results used to estimate the $Z_{o}$ of the asymmetric stripline.
[src:microstrip-design/stripline] $V_{c}$ is the speed of light in a vacuum.
[src:microstrip-design/stripline] $H_{L}$ and $H_{U}$ are measured from center of the conductor to the lower and upper ground plane, respectively.
[src:microstrip-design/stripline] Co and Lo are the capacitance and inductance per unit length of the associated transmission line.
[src:microstrip-design/stripline] If there is no dielectric in the asymmetric stripline, then the stripline looks like a microstrip with a dielectric of air, $\varepsilon =1$ , inside a metallic enclosure.
[src:microstrip-design/stripline] This permits the air characteristic impedance, $Z_{o}^{a}$ , to be calculated using microstrip metallic enclosure equations.
[src:microstrip-design/stripline] The accuracy of this $Z_{o}$ estimation is quantified and listed in the microstrip metallic enclosure equations.
[src:microstrip-design/stripline] Since microstrip loss calculation are not directly a function of dielectric constant and geometry or metallic cover height, microstrip loss equations may also be used for stripline losses by treating εre as a constant equal to εr.
